text: DOI: 10.1002/cbic.200600375 A Genomic Screening Approach to the Structure-Guided Identification of Drug Candidates from Natural Sources Andreas Hornung,[a] Marcelo Bertazzo,[b] Agnieszka Dziarnowski,[a] Kathrin Schneider,[b] Katrin Welzel,[a] Sven-Eric Wohlert,[a] Meike Holzenk!mpfer,[a] Graeme J. Nicholson,[c] Andreas Bechthold,[d] Roderich D. S*ssmuth,[b] Andreas Vente,[a] and Stefan Pelzer*[a] The potential of actinomycetes to produce natural products has been exploited for decades. Recent genomic sequence analyses have revealed a previously unrecognized biosynthetic potential and diversity. In order to rationally exploit this potential, we have developed a sequence-guided genetic screening strategy. In this “genome mining” approach, genes that encode tailoring enzymes from natural product biosyntheses pathways serve as indicator genes for the identification of strains that have the genetic po- tential to produce natural products of interest. We chose halo- genases, which are known to be involved in the synthesis of halo- There continues to be an urgent medical need to discover and develop new drugs. This has become critical for anti-infective agents because infectious diseases are the second leading cause of death worldwide.[1] The discovery of the first case of a Staphylococcus aureus strain that is fully resistant to vancomy- cin,[2] and the fact that up to 60 % of S. aureus strains world- wide are methicillin resistant[3] exemplify this serious problem. Traditionally the development of anti-infectives has been do- indeed 79 % of all minated by natural product compounds; Gantibacterials and antibacterial lead candidates in the period between 1981 and 2002 originated from natural compounds.[4] In particular, compounds that are produced by soil bacteria, such as actinomycetes have been a rich source of commercial drugs.

In spite of the success of natural products as a source for drug leads, most pharmaceutical companies have downgraded or even stopped activities in the natural product sector in favor of organic synthesis methods. This strategy change is due to the properties of natural product research in regards to the drug development process. The properties that have put natural products at a disadvantage include: 1) the screening conditions and compound requirements, which differ signifi- cantly from synthetic library-based approaches, 2) the rediscov- ery of known compounds from the screening of natural prod- uct libraries, 3) the structural complexity of many natural prod- ucts, and 4) the difficulties incorporating natural product struc- tures into semisynthetic approaches. From PCR screening of 550 randomly selected actinomycetes strains, we identified 103 novel putative halogenase genes. A phylogenetic analysis of the corresponding putative halogenases, and the determination of their sequential context with mass spectrometric analysis of cul- tures filtrates revealed a distinct correlation between the se- quence and secondary metabolite class of the halometabolite. The described screening strategy allows rapid access to novel natural products with predetermined structural properties. natural products as drug leads is hampered by the high pro- duction costs of natural products, which is caused by low pro- duction yields and complex purification processes.[5] In this contribution, we describe a genetic screening strat- egy for the prediction of the biosynthetic potential of whole strain collections. This approach sets the stage for the discov- ery of novel subtypes of known compound classes, and could lead to the discovery of new compounds. Our strategy is based on the paradigm that natural products with identical or similar structural elements are produced by biosynthetic pathways that contain highly homologous en- zymes. Therefore, genes that encode such enzymes are suita- ble targets to predict the biosynthetic potential of different strains. This has been demonstrated for enzymes that are in- volved in the backbone biosynthesis of polyketides.[6–9] Howev- er, because these enzymes are typical for the synthesis of a dis- tinct chemical structural class, they are not as useful for broad- er chemical classes; markers that cover different structural classes would be more useful for a broader, more structurally diverse global screening strategy. Therefore, our approach is based on the tailoring enzymes involved in natural product bi- osyntheses, because they are responsible for the introduction and generation of diversity in several structural classes. In addi- tion, their sequential gene relationship is characteristic enough to distinguish the biosynthetic pathways of multiple structural compound classes. In this contribution, we show an example of using conserved primers that target FADH2-dependent halo- genase genes with a described specificity for phenol and pyr- role derivatives; these are involved in the elaboration of differ- ent natural product scaffolds.[10–12] The importance of the reac- tion that is catalyzed by these gene products in generating Gdiversity is apparent by the 4000 chlorinated or brominated natural product compounds that are known from a variety of structural classes.[13] We have demonstrated that a genetic screening for tailoring enzymes can be successfully used to identify producer strains of natural products that belong to a broad range of different structural classes by using a single screening process. The ap- proach presented here opens possibilities for the genetic profiling of strain collections to identify strains that have the genetic potential to produce novel target compounds. Such a preselection dramatically reduces the number of strains that have to be investigated for the identification of alternative pro- ducer strains or derivative producers of target substances. Genetic screening for novel putative halogenase genes.

In order to identify producer strains that harbor a certain sub- class of halogenating enzymes, and thus that contain the Ggenetic potential for the synthesis of halometabolites, a PCR- based approach with specific primer probes was chosen. Ap- propriate pairs of degenerated primers were deduced from highly conserved regions of six FADH2-dependent halogenases (Figure 1). These enzymes have specificities for diverse phenol- and pyrrole-containing metabolites from different actinomy- cetes strains (Figure 2). Primer optimization experiments resulted in a single primer pair (Halo-B4-FW and Halo-B7-RV) and yielded positive results when the total DNAs of the six halometabolite-producing con- trol strains were screened in PCR experiments. This primer pair was used for the subsequent PCR screening of 550 strains, B 2007 Wiley-VCH Verlag GmbH & Co. KGaA, Weinheim which were randomly selected from a comprehensive actino- mycetes strain collection. The hit rate was 20 % for amplified PCR fragments with the expected size of approximately 550 base pairs. In total, 103 PCR fragments were sequenced. A BLAST analysis of the deduced sequences of the PCR products revealed that less than 2 % of the fragments were false positive with homologies to other genes. A phylogenetic analysis of the protein sequences of all newly identified putative halogen- ases displayed large sequence diversity with identities from below 10 % to up to 100 %. Several novel putative halogenases show homologies to previously described halogenases; like the halogenases identified from glycopeptide antibiotic (GPA) biosynthetic clusters (Figure 3 A, B). In contrast, genes were identified that encode typical halogenase sequence elements, which cannot be allocated to any other known halogenase subgroup.

The genetic information obtained for 35 genes, from which the corresponding gene products display significant similarities to halogenases on the sequence level was further expanded by primer-walking sequencing on cosmids from respective ge- nomic libraries. This was performed in order to determine the genetic context into which the respective putative halogenase genes were embedded. A sequence comparison revealed that the genes adjacent to (both upstream and downstream) the corresponding putative halogenase gene displayed a signifi- cant homology to genes that are indicative of a distinct bio- synthetic gene cluster. These gene clusters could often be as- signed to the synthesis of a specific natural product structure. From this finding, it was predicted that actinomycetes that harbor putative halogenase sequences in a particular genetic context have the potential to synthesize compounds that belong to the respective natural product class. This hypothesis was tested by using the strain collections described above, from which a subclass of newly identified pu- tative GPA-producer strains was analyzed in more detail. On the amino acid level, the halogenase sequences from these strains displayed 64–98 % similarity to halogenases involved in (vancomycin-like)[14] and type V (complestatin- GPA type I like)[15] biosynthesis as shown in Figure 3.

Furthermore, the newly identified gene loci from five strains (Cb2429, Cb2364, Cb2192, Cb2023 and Cb2312, Figure 4) showed genetic organizations similar to the respective sub- types of GPA’s biosynthetic gene clusters. In all type I GPA gene clusters, as found in strains Cb2429 and Cb2364, a P450 monooxygenase and a glycosyltransferase gene are located upstream and downstream of the corresponding halogenase gene, respectively. In contrast, the putative halogenase genes with the highest homologies to genes from type V glyco- Gpeptide biosynthetic clusters, like those identified in strains Cb2192, Cb2023 and Cb2312, are located between an antiport- er and a P450 monooxygenase gene (Figure 4). The accession numbers of these newly identified halogenases can be found in the Experimental Section (PCR-based screening of genomic DNA for halogenase genes). In addition to the assignment of sequences to previously Gdescribed GPA biosynthesis gene clusters, one other GPA bio- synthetic gene cluster was identified. The sequence analysis of adjacent genes in one sub- group revealed that the respective putative halogenase genes are located next to genes involved in the production of aro- matic polyketides. As an example, upstream from the putative halogenase gene from strain Cb2544 is a gene with homology to the transcriptional activator RubS (AAM97369) from the aro- matic polyketide biosynthesis of rubromycin, and downstream lies a gene with homology to GrhO10 (AAM33668), a reductase involved in the formation of the aromatic polyketide griseorho- din.[16] The putative involvement of the identified halogenase gene in the PKS biosynthesis was further supported by a PCR screening experiment. Here, a conserved primer pair that is specific for genes that encode the a domain of the b-ketoacyl- synthase (KSa) of type II (PKS II) polyketide synthases[17] was used in PCR experiments (see Experimental Section, PCR-based the identification of PKS II genes). By using screening for cosmid 2544-3B10, which encodes the putative halogenase gene of strain Cb2544 as a PCR template, a characteristic 600 bp DNA fragment could be successfully amplified. The de- duced amino acid sequence displays significant similarities to PKS II-specific b-ketoacyl-synthase a domains (KSa). The simi- larity (71 %) could be observed to the rubromycin-specific KSa domain RubA (AGG03067). Similar results could be achieved on further cosmids that encode other PKS II-related putative halogenase genes. B 2007 Wiley-VCH Verlag GmbH & Co. KGaA, Weinheim

Two other comprehensive subgroups with putative halogen- ase sequences were identified that cannot be correlated to known halogenase subfamilies. The sequencing of adjacent genes, and the supporting hybridizing experiments indicate that the putative halogenase genes from one of the two sub- groups might be involved in the production of halogenated macrolide antibiotics (Figure 3 B). Furthermore, putative halo- genase genes were identified (Figure 3 A, B) that have signifi- cant homologies to their published counterparts from gene clusters encoding metabolites like lipoglycodepsipeptides (ra- moplanin),[18] enediyne antibiotics (C1027),[19] aminocoumarin (simocyclinone)[20–21] and ansamycin antibiotics antibiotics (naphthomycin).[22] Mass spectrometric screening for halogenase-containing GPA-producing wild-type strains In order to evaluate the biosynthetic potential for the produc- tion of halogenated natural products, a mass spectrometric screening was performed on strains that were preselected by the above-mentioned PCR screening. An analytical proof for the biosynthetic product is mandatory, because genetic evi- dence for a particular gene does not necessarily coincide with the production of a corresponding gene product. Identification of novel halogen- ated aromatic polyketides by heterologous expression

Heterologous expression of com- plete natural product biosyn- thetic gene clusters is an elegant method to elucidate the role of genes and gene clusters in me- tabolite biosynthesis.[24] Because gene clusters for PKS II biosyn- theses usually do not exceed the size of a typical cosmid insert of 40 kb, we decided to transfer various cosmids that harbor hal- ogenases and genes with ho- mology to PKS II biosynthesis into the expression host S. albus J1074. compound, CBS40, with a molecular mass of [M+H] + = 550 was detected by HPLC–MS in an ethyl acetate ex- tract of transconjugant Cb3817, in the untransformed but not ChemBioChem 2007, 8, 757 – 766 Genome-Based Natural Product Screening Scheme 1. Gexpression host (Figure 6 A and B). CB3817 was generated by transferring cosmid 2544-3B10 which carries both PKS II and the 2544 halogenase genes. The halogenated product, CBS40, could not be the product of a silent gene cluster of S. albus for two reasons. First, genetic screening experiments verified that S. albus does not contain a corresponding FADH2-dependent halogenase gene (data not shown). Second, the transfer of cosmid 2544-3B10 into alternative hosts, such as S. coelicolor also led to the production of the identical compound CBS40 (data not shown). Compound CBS40 was purified from the cul- ture filtrate (5 L) by ethyl acetate extraction and column chro- matography. The compound was isolated (10 mg) and structur- ally characterized by NMR spectroscopy (Figure 6 A, Tables S2– S4). As predicted by the genetic analysis, the compound is a halogenated aromatic polyketide. Database searches (SciFinder Scholar, Version 2004, American Chemical Society) revealed that the structure of this compound is novel. A structural com- parison to related compounds shows an apparent homology lysolipin or cervinomy- to polycyclic xanthones, for example, cin.[25–26] Polycyclic xanthones such as cervinomycin, have been described as being highly active against Gram-positive bacte- ria.[27] Likewise, CBS40 also displays extremely high antibacterial activity against various Gram-positive bacteria with MIC values of 0.3–10 ng mL(cid:1)1 (Figure 6 C). Surprisingly, CBS40 possesses significant antibacterial activity against the Gram-negative E. coli ATCC 10536 whereas other previously described polycyc- lic xanthones, such as lysolipin do not exhibit activity against non-cell-membrane-damaged Gram-negative enterobacteria.[25]

Actinomycetes are a rich source for enzymes and secondary metabolites that are encoded by biosynthetic gene clus- ters.[28–29] Compounds from natural sources, particularly bacteri- al cultures, have been identified in screening campaigns in the in the more industry for decades. In contrast, estimations show that only a small proportion of all naturally occurring antibacterial agents have been discovered so far;[30] this suggests that there is still an enormous potential to use the structural diversity of natural products. One approach to achieve this goal is the var- iation of media and cultivation conditions of microorganisms; this can yield more than a dozen unrelated novel metabolites from a single strain after cultivation under various condi- tions.[31] However, the large number of cultures to be handled, and the even larger number of samples to be analyzed that result from this strategy sets limits for its application. There- fore, new technologies that enable a systematic re-evaluation and preselection of strains from the large bacterial strain col- lections are needed. A combination of such strategies will help to re-establish natural products as an important source for drug development.

Genome-sequencing projects on different actinomycetes have revealed a vast number of natural product biosynthetic gene clusters in each genome. Furthermore, the number of predicted metabolites is much higher than the number of me- tabolites that have been identified from such well-character- ized strains.[32–34] The sequence-guided prediction and subse- quent identification of metabolites that were novel or previ- ously unknown for certain strains, for example, siderophores from Streptomyces coelicolor[35–36] and pentalenolactone or pen- taene from Streptomyces avermitilis,[37–38] clearly demonstrate that these orphan gene clusters should not necessarily be con- sidered to be genetic waste. Our approach is based on a systematic genetic profiling of an actinomycetes strain collection for the existence of genes where the putative gene products display significant similari- ties to a certain class of halogenating enzymes. Halogenation is an important feature for the biological activity of a large number of different natural products.[39–41] The interest in and knowledge of halogenating enzymes is increasing rapidly. There are two subtypes of halogenases that are known to be involved in the biosynthesis of secondary metabolites: the FADH2-dependent halogenases that act upon aromatic or het- eroaromatic rings, which is the subtype that was used in this study, and the recently discovered non-heme FeII halogenases, which act on aliphatic groups.[42] This second novel class of hal- ogenases could also be used for the described screening ap- proach. This might allow for the identification of completely different classes of compounds, including non-halogenated metabolites, because biological chlorination is a cryptic strat- egy for cyclopropyl ring formation.[43]

PCR-based genetic screening led to the identification of genes that encode putative FADH2-dependent halogenases in 20 % of a random collection of actinomycetes, with specificities for phenols and pyrrole derivatives. The surprising prevalence of biosynthetic gene clusters that comprise halogenase se- quences in actinomycetes clearly exceeds the number of halo- genated metabolites that have been isolated from this species so far. A single primer pair was sufficient to perform this halo- genase screening campaign. The fact that homologues of nearly all known FADH2-dependent halogenases of the phenol/ pyrrole type have been identified, clearly accounts for the broad applicability of this approach. In addition, more than 40 novel genes that encode putative halogenases have been identified which cannot be assigned to any of the known structural subclasses. These genes are either part of hitherto unknown biosynthetic gene clusters that are involved in the biosynthesis of known metabolites, or they might be involved in the biosynthesis of completely novel metabolites. A relevant portion (> 8 %) of the identified putative halogenase genes dis- plays high homology to halogenases that are characteristic for the biosynthesis of GPAs (type I and V). This observation was verified by the analytical proof of the production of halogenat- ed glycopeptides by means of HPLC–ESI-MS/MS. The sequence analysis of the selected halogenase marker genes was used to discriminate between the different GPA subtypes, as exempli- fied by the prediction and purification of a vancomycin-type GPA. The PCR-based screening strategy described in this contribu- tion opens the possibility to identify producers of metabolite classes even without knowing the underlying biosynthetic and genetic principle of the respective compound class. Here, we B 2007 Wiley-VCH Verlag GmbH & Co. KGaA, Weinheim

were able to predict the biosynthesis potential of a producer of a novel polycyclic xanthone by genetic screening, even though the exact biosynthetic pathway for such compounds had not been described. Heterologous expression of cosmids that harbor the genes that were identified by genetic screen- ing proved to be a powerful method for the detection and production of such unknown compounds. The potential of this strategy is demonstrated by the finding that our newly discov- ered compound, CBS40 is active against Gram-positive bacte- ria, as are other polycyclic xanthones, and additionally, it dis- plays activity against Gram-negative bacteria. In conclusion, we demonstrated that a PCR-based genetic screening that targets marker genes from biosynthetic gene clusters is a powerful tool for the rapid identification of natural product producer strains even from large strain collections. Furthermore, as a proof of principle, we could show that a phylogenetic analysis of the amplified PCR products allows an exact prediction of the structural class of natural products being synthesized by an individual strain. The nature of two synthesized metabolites from the NRPS (nonribosomal peptide synthetase) and PKS biosynthesis pathways has been shown by their isolation and structural elucidation with NMR spectros- copy methods. The presented screening strategy is flexible and can easily be adapted to any natural product class, even if the genetic blueprint is not known. In the future, genetic screening will represent a valuable tool that complements already well- established technologies for natural product discovery with mi- croorganisms. This “genome mining” approach will allow the evaluation and preselection of useful strains from large collec- tions, which can be analyzed in more detail if necessary. This approach provides a method to make natural products screen- ing more time- and cost-efficient and potentially more success- ful.

Bacterial strains, vectors and culture conditions: E. coli DH5a and E. coli XL1 Blue (Stratagene, Heidelberg, Germany) were used for cloning experiments and grown as described previously.[44] Genom- ic cosmid libraries were constructed in E. coli DH5a by using pO J436[45] as a cosmid vector. For DNA extraction mycelium was embedded in agarose, then the DNA was partially digested and isolated; this yielded fragments with an average size greater than 35 kb. Robotically produced high-density colony arrays (Hybond N +; Amersham Pharmacia) were used for the screening of 2304 cosmid clones with strain-specific halogenase gene probes by using standard nonradioactive hybridization procedures. Inverse- sequencing of cosmids starting from the sequenced PCR product yielded the complete halogenase gene sequence information by means of open-reading frame analysis. Streptomyces albus J1074 was used as a host for heterologous cluster expression and culti- vated as preculture in tryptone soy broth (TSB; Becton, Dickinson and Co., Sparks, USA). R5[45] was used as a production medium for Streptomyces cultivation. PCR-based screening of genomic DNA for putative halogenase genes: Genomic DNA from actinomycetes was isolated by using the NucleoSpinP kit from Macherey–Nagel (D*ren, Germany) as de- scribed in the manual. PCR-based screening for the identification of putative PKS II genes: For the identification of genes encoding putative PKS II- type a domains of the b-ketoacyl-synthase, specific primers have been used as described by Mets!-Ketel! et al. 2002.[46] Genomic or cosmid DNAs were screened with the primers PKS II-FW 5’-TSG- GCSTGCTTCGAYGCSATC-3’ and PKS II-RV 5’-TGGAANCCGCCGAABCC- GGCT-3’. A 50 mL PCR reaction contains: 5 mL 10 Q PCR buffer (Qiagen, Hilden, Germany), 1 mL PKS II-FW and PKS II-RV primers (30 pmol mL(cid:1)1) each, 4 mL dNTPs (10 mm), 2.5 mL DMSO, 0.5 mL Taq Polymerase (5 u mL(cid:1)1, Qiagen, Hilden, Germany), 1 mL genomic or cosmid DNA (ca. 0.2 mg), 35 mL H2O. The PCR was performed in a MJ Research cycler (PTC-225) under the following cycling condi- tions: 1) 2 min at 95 8C for 1 cycle; 2) 1 min at 95 8C, 2 min at 72 8C, 1.5 min at 72 8C for 30 cycles; 3) 5 min at 72 8C for 1 cycle. Positive fragments with the expected size of approximately 600 bp were subcloned into the pBluescriptP vector (Stratagene) and se- quenced.

Screening for glycopeptide metabolites: Bacterial strains were cultivated in R5-medium in Erlenmeyer flasks (500 mL) with one baffle on a rotary shaker at 30 8C and 160 rpm. The preculture was incubated for 48 h. Subsequently, the cultures were inoculated with 5 vol % of preculture and were incubated for 120 h. Afterward, the fermentation samples were centrifuged and the supernatants were used for direct analysis of glycopeptides by means of HPLC– ESI-MS. HPLC–MS analyses were performed on an HPLC Agi- lent 1100 HPLC system (Agilent Technologies, Waldbronn, Germa- ny) coupled to a Bruker Esquire 3000 + (Bruker-Daltonics, Bremen, Germany). An aliquot of the samples (100 mL) was injected onto a HPLC column (125 mm Q 4 mm) which was packed with 5 mm Pur- ospher RP-18e (Merck, Darmstadt, Germany). The samples were an- alyzed by using a gradient (solvent A: 0.1 % TFA, solvent B: acetoni- trile/0.1 % TFA) (min to min, % B; 0.0 to 1.0, 0 % B; 1.0 to 3.0, 10 % B; 3.0 to 8.0, 12 % B; 8.0 to 14.0, 40 % B) with a flow rate of 1.5 mL min(cid:1)1. Mass spectra were recorded in a mass range of m/z 50–3000 in positive-ion mode. ChemBioChem 2007, 8, 757 – 766 B 2007 Wiley-VCH Verlag GmbH & Co. KGaA, Weinheim

Isolation of compound CB2364-I: For the large-scale fermentation (30 L) of Cb2364 (500 mL Erlenmeyer flaks) the same culture condi- tions were used as in the screening. Hyflo Super-cel (3 %) was added to the fermentation and the broth was separated from the mycelium by multiple sheet filtrations. The culture filtrate was sub- jected to a XAD1180 column (60 Q 8 cm) and separated by using step gradients with decreasing polarity (water/MeOH: 1:0; 4:2; 3:2; 2:3; 2:4; 0:1). Glycopeptide-containing fractions (HPLC–MS control) were subjected to a Biogel P2 column (60 Q 4 cm), washed with de- ionized water and chromatographed (deionized water/0.1 % TFA). Finally, analytically pure glycopeptide was obtained by preparative reversed-phase HPLC–MS with a prepLCMS Merck-Hitachi HTP-MS System (Merck, Darmstadt, Germany). The separation was per- formed by using a purospher-star RP-18e (100 Q 2.5 cm; 5 mm) with solvent A (0.1 % TFA) and solvent B (acetonitril, 0.1 % TFA). The gra- dient was (0.0–1.0 min, 0 % B; 1.0–3.0 min, 10 % B; 3.0–8.0 min, 12 % B; 8.0–14.0 min, 40 % B) with a flow rate of 15 mL min(cid:1)1. Mass spectra were recorded in positive-ion mode. The yield of the isolat- ed peptide metabolite was 5 mg.

Structure determination of compound CB2364-I: FTICR–ESI-MS spectra were recorded as single measurements on an APEX II FTICR Mass Spectrometer (Bruker–Daltonics, Bremen, Germany). To en- hance mass accuracy, spectra were measured with internal mass standard (Ultramark, Ventron, Karlsruhe, Germany). NMR spectros- copy experiments were recorded on an AMX600 NMR spectrome- ter (Bruker, Karlsruhe, Germany) equipped with a triple-resonance probehead (5 mm) with z-gradients. Structural assignment of CB2364-I was performed by evaluation of 2D NMR experiments (COSY, TOCSY, HSQC, HMBC and NOESY). Isolation of compound CBS40: For heterologous expression, gene clusters were transferred into Streptomyces albus J1074 by inter- generic conjugation.[45] For the expression of compound CBS40, cosmid 2544-3B10, a pO J436[45] derivative carrying a chromosomal insert of approximately 40 kb which encodes both PKS II and halo- genase genes was transferred. Transconjugants that harbor the Grespective cosmids were grown as precultures at 28 8C for 48 h in TSB that contained apramycin (25 mg mL(cid:1)1) on a rotary shaker at 160 rpm. R5 medium (5 L) that contained apramycin (25 mg mL(cid:1)1) was used for production. Transconjugants as main cultures were cultivated in flasks that contained medium (100 mL) for 120 h at 28 8C.

Cultures of the CBS40 producing S. albus transconjugant Cb3817, which carried the chromosomally integrated cosmid 2544–3B10 were harvested, adjusted to pH 3 with HCl, and the culture filtrate was extracted twice with ethyl acetate. The evaporated crude ex- tract was chromatographed on a silica gel 60 column with CH2Cl2/ MeOH (9:1). The fractions that contained CBS40 were pooled and chromatographed on a second silica gel 60 column with CH2Cl2/ MeOH (7:3). The pooled fractions were then chromatographed on a Sephadex LH-20 column with CH2Cl2/MeOH (7:3) to yield 10 mg of CBS40 as a yellow solid. The antibacterial activity of CBS40 was determined in vitro in broth dilution assays. This procedure has been described elsewhere.[47] HPLC–DAD-MS analysis and NMR spectroscopy of compound CBS40: HPLC–DAD-MS analysis was performed on a Waters Alli- ance 2790 HT separations module (Waters GmbH, Eschborn, Ger- many) coupled to a Waters PDA 996 detector and a Micromass Q- TOF2 mass spectrometer (Waters, formerly Micromass, Eschborn, Germany). High-resolution mass spectra (ESI-HRMS) were acquired by using the same Micromass QTOF2 mass spectrometer.

Aliquots of the samples (20 mL) were injected onto a HPLC column (Grom Sil 120 ODS-4 HE, 40 Q 4 mm, 3 mm, (Grom Chromatography GmbH, Rottenburg-Hailfingen, Germany). The samples were ana- lyzed by a gradient [solvent A: 0.1 % formic acid in water, sol- vent B: acetonitrile; 0.0 min at 98 % A then 1 mL min(cid:1)1 to 5.0 min at 16.7 % A, then 1 mL min(cid:1)1 (curve 1) to 6.0 min at 4.0 % A, then 1.7 mL min(cid:1)1 (curve 6) to 8.0 min at 4 % A, then 1.7 mL min(cid:1)1 (curve 6) to 8.5 min at 98 % A, then 1.0 mL min(cid:1)1 (curve 6) to 10.0 min at 98 % A. Mass spectra were recorded in a mass range of m/z 50– 1800 in positive ion mode. 1H and 13C NMR spectra were recorded on a Bruker Avance 600 at 600.01 MHz and 150.87 MHz, respectively. The structure of CBS40 was elucidated by using 1D spectra and 2D homo- and heteronu- clear correlation experiments (1H, 13C, DEPT45, DEPT90, DEPT135, COSY45, HMQC, HMBC) and by comparison with the NMR spectros- copy data for Lysolipin I.[48] NMR spectroscopy data are shown in Tables S2–S4.
